snippet.title: LearnNext Class 9 Mathematics l Number Systems l Real Numbers
snippet.description:
The collection of all rational numbers and irrational numbers together is the set of real numbers. It is represented by R. A real number is either a rational number or an irrational number.

In a division, if remainder becomes zero after certain stage, then the decimal expansion is terminating.
If the remainder never becomes zero but repeats after certain stage, then the decimal expansion is non-terminating recurring.

A rational number can be expressed as its decimal expansion. The decimal expansion of a rational number is either terminating or non-terminating recurring. The decimal expansion of an irrational number is non-terminating non-recurring. Every real number can be represented on a number line uniquely. Conversely every point on the number line represents one and only one real number.

The process of visualisation of representing a decimal expansion on the number line is known as the process of successive magnification.

snippet.title: Tissues - Animal Tissues - Science - Class 9
snippet.description:
Types of Animal Tissues include epithelial tissue, connective tissue, muscular tissue and nervous tissue.Epithelial tissues form a protective layer. Different types of epithelial tissues are classified based on their shape and function. Squamous epithelium are found in the organs to provide mechanical support. Columnar epithelium are found in the lining of the organs to facilitate the movement of nutrients. Glandular epithelium are found in the glands to produce secretions. Ciliated epithelium are found in the lining of the respiratory tract. Cuboidal epithelium are found in organs to provide mechanical support. Stratified epithelium are found in places of wear and tear. Connective tissue connects different organs. Different types of connective tissues are classified based on their shape and functions. Blood is a type of  fluid connective tissue. Read more at http://learnnext.com/lesson/CBSE-IX-Science-Animal-Tissues.htm

snippet.title: Class 9 | Maths | Probability | Experimental Approach
snippet.description:
Class 9 | Maths | Probability | Experimental Approach

In this module, you will learn to define probability and the basic terminology related to it.
In our day-to-day life, we come across statements like:
I have worked really hard; I hope to get an A in my Science project.
Chances look bright to our winning the inter-college football match.
There may be a hike in the diesel prices.
The gold prices will probably fall after the festival season.
The stock market is likely to fall.
The words hope, chances, maybe, probably, and likely used in these statements involve an element of uncertainty or chance.
These words are all synonyms used to indicate the term probability.
Probability is the likelihood of something occurring.
The different board games such as Snakes and Ladders, Ludo, Tambola, and Monopoly involve probability.
The popular game – cricket, begins with the tossing of a coin, which also involves probability.

snippet.description:
Class 9 | Maths | Quadrilaterals | Midpoint Theorem 

In this module, you will learn to prove and apply the Mid-point theorem.
The theorem says that the line segment joining the mid-points of the two sides of a triangle is parallel to the third side and equal to half the third side.
Let ABC be the given triangle in which P and Q are mid-points of sides AB and AC respectively.
We have to prove that line PQ is parallel to side BC and PQ is half of BC.
Draw a line CR parallel to BA such that it meets PQ produced at R.
Here, we’ll prove that the quadrilateral BCRP is a parallelogram
Let’s begin with the proof.
By construction, we have drawn CR parallel to BA, and from the figure, AC acts as a transversal for them.
This implies angle QAP is equal to angle QCR as they form a pair of alternate interior angles. Denote this as equation 1.
Also, AQ is equal to QC, since Q is the mid-point of side AC.
Also, angle AQP is equal to angle CQR, since they form a pair of vertically opposite angles.

snippet.title: Class 9 | Science | Motion | Introduction to Motion
snippet.description:
Class 9 | Science | Motion | Introduction to Motion

In everyday life, you see some objects at rest and others in motion. Birds fly, horses gallop, water flows through rivers and cars move. You say these are in motion. Thus, the motion is a state of an object in which, there is a change in its position with respect to its surroundings.
When a car race starts, the position of each car participating in the race changes relative to the stands, and spectators. This is because the cars are in a state of motion.
What happens when we compare the state of two or more than two objects?

For instance, let us consider the state of a car driver:
Is he at rest or in motion?

It is difficult to answer this question. This is because, with respect to the car, the driver is at rest but with respect to the other things around, he is in motion. 
Thus, the states of rest and motion of bodies are relative. Absolute states of rest or motion do not exist.

snippet.title: Class 9 | Science | Natural Resources | Biogeochemical Cycle
snippet.description:
Class 9 | Science | Natural Resources | Biogeochemical Cycle

In this module, you will learn about biogeochemical cycles – the water cycle and the nitrogen cycle.
What is the biogeochemical cycle?
The cycling of chemicals between the biological and the geological world is called biogeochemical cycle.
The biotic and abiotic components of the biosphere constantly interact through these cycles.
These interactions enable the transfer of nutrients between living organisms and nonliving environment.
What are the four most important biogeochemical cycles?
The four most important biogeochemical cycles are water cycle, nitrogen cycle, carbon cycle, and oxygen cycle.

snippet.title: Class 9 | Science | Structure of the Atom | Atomic Models
snippet.description:
Class 9 | Science | Structure of the Atom | Atomic Models

In this module, you will learn about Thomson’s Atomic Model. 
Are the charged particles arranged in any particular manner? Are the charged particles spread throughout the atom or are they concentrated in one place? To answer these questions, let’s go back in time…
Dalton’s atomic theory stated that an atom was indivisible and indestructible. However, in 1886, Goldstein came upon positively charged radiations in a gas discharge, which he termed as canal rays. These radiations led to the discovery of the proton. The mass of a proton was about 2000 times that of an electron and it carried a positive charge. 
Around the year 1900, J. J. Thomson conducted experiments on the beams of particles inside a glass tube called a cathode ray tube. He found that the particles were attracted to the positive terminal of the tube. Thomson concluded that the particles must be negatively charged and called these particles ‘electrons’. An electron has a negligible mass and has a charge of minus one.

snippet.title: Class 9 | Maths | Polynomial | Remainder Theorem
snippet.description:
Class 9 | Maths | Polynomial | Remainder Theorem

In this module, you will learn about remainder theorem. 
The Remainder theorem states that,
If a polynomial p(x) is a polynomial in x, and p(x) is divided by x-a, then the remainder is p(a).
Let’s now see how we can verify this theorem.
It is given that,
 The dividend = p(x) and
 The divisor = x-a.
Let,
 The quotient be q(x) and
 The remainder be R.
On the basis of the division rule, you can derive the equation:
p(x)=(x-a)q(x)+R
This equation is true for all real values. Therefore, if we assume x=a, then
p(a)=(a-a)×q(a)+R
On solving, you get:
R=p(a)

snippet.title: Class 9 | Science | Natural Resources
snippet.description:
Class 9 | Science | Natural Resources

The water that is found above the earth in the form of cloud and below the earth as ground water together forms hydrosphere . Hydrosphere constitutes 75% of the Earth’s surface.
In this module, you learned that:
• The land, the water and the air are the natural resources available on the Earth.
• The solid outermost layer of the Earth’s crust and the rigid upper part of its mantle is called the lithosphere.
• The Earth’s surface, above it as clouds and below it as ground water is called the hydrosphere.
• The air that covers the Earth like a blanket is called the atmosphere.
• The region where the atmosphere, the hydrosphere and the lithosphere interact and supports life is called the biosphere.
• The biosphere has two components: biotic and abiotic.
•  Living organisms constitute the biotic component of the biosphere.
• The air, the water and the soil constitute the abiotic component of the biosphere.
